ID:1237610_10101661552741793
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:I did not like Skyfall.

(Possible spoilers - will try not to give anything away, but let's face it: There's enough holes in the movie that there's really not much to spoil)

Anybody else severely disappointed by Skyfall? Normally I can find the good in movies, no matter how horrible critics say they are. This time, I must say Skyfall is the most disappointing movie of the year. Were my expectations set too high? Perhaps, but let's examine the Downfall.

(a) There were too many holes in the plot. It feels like there were many questions that the movie set us up to ask; that it made us feel like it was going to answer, but ultimately did not follow through. It feels almost as if the director ran short of production budget halfway through, and said "Alright, stop filming - that's Good Enough"

(b) The lack of a(ny decent amount of screen-time for the) Bond girl. She was actually so irrelevant that I actually spent three-quarters of the movie wondering who the Bond girl is. Is the French girl? The Latina? Or the African-American? Needless to say, I have already forgotten her face. 

(c) They destroyed a perfectly good classical car. JUST for the hell of it. For Car Aficionados out there, this struck a nerve.

(d) They Only destroyed 1 expensive car, and only 1.5 buildings (+a sewage tunnel). All in very implausible ways. WHAT HAPPENED TO THE PRODUCTION VALUE?? 

(e) Bond Car - Or lack thereof. Let's review - Casino Royale: Aston Martin DBS V12. Quantum of Solace: Aston Martin DBS V12. Skyfall: Aston Martin DB-Wha??? 
In all seriousness, Eon Productions, the DB5 would have made a great Bond car - 50 years ago. In this day and age, my neighbor's soccer-mom mini-van has more power than that thing. Today, the 2014 Aston Martin Vanquish is available in all its glorious five hundred and sixty-odd bhp. WHY WAS THAT NOT IN THE MOVIE? In fact, the more exciting car from the movie was the "company" Jag that Bond drove for all of 10 seconds. And it's not even a British car! It's owned by Tata Motors.

(f) FACEPALM. Every time they try to say ANYTHING Computer Science related. The screen-writers need a technical reviewer that didn't get his education from the University of Hollywood. It's damn right insulting.

(g) Bond. For me, Daniel Craig's Bond appeal comes in two-folds. First, he has descended from the conventional super-human Bond-Invincibility to the bleeding mortal-man, to which we can all relate. Second, his defiance towards rules and authority makes him an interesting character to watch. To both points, these were lessened in SKyfall. (He falls into a frozen lake and comes out seemingly unphased.. He spends half the movie following M around and calling her Ma'am..)
  

I want the two-and-a-half-hours of my life back.      Thanks for reading :P

Name:2013 Scion FR-S "Bringing Sport Back" Launch Commercial
Story:N/A
Message:Went playing with cars today, and while admittedly I spent the better part of the day drooling between an M6 and a GTR, my happiest moment was realizing that car manufacturers are finally starting to build cars like this again:

The FR-S/BRZ is a brilliantly awesome car. Unbelievably low center of gravity, and practically designed from the ground up to be near-perfectly balanced. With this car, there is a rare poise to be found in the composition of where rubber meets asphalt; a harmony between the engine and chassis, and the steering and suspension. This is a beautifully seductive ride.  

In other words - I want one in manual, and Asphalt black.

Name:The case for open borders
Story:N/A
Message:I often disagree with Bryan Caplan, a predictably orthodox economist, but I'm delighted that he favors "open borders," a policy I've favored since I was about 12. No one who believes in freedom can reasonably oppose this view. This means that opposition to open borders is logically inconsistent with a belief in natural rights and human freedom. End of story.

ID:2730525_10102229587615368
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:In response to a query from my dear friend Catherine Yvonne, I cheated and listed more than 10 books, and took more than the ten minutes she allocated. :) However, here are a few of the many books that have profoundly affected me at various times since 1948, when I learned to read. Thank you to my teacher, Mrs. Patrick, RIP. She was wonderful.

Capital in the Twenty-First Century

Escape from Freedom

Einstein: His Life and Universe

Johnny Got His Gun

Levels of Knowing and Existence: Studies in General Semantics

Men of Mathematics

On Liberty

Siddhartha 

The Art of Loving

The Big Short 

The Book of Woodcraft and Indian Lore 

The Girl, the Gold Watch, and Everything

The Kite Runner 

The Last Lion: Winston Spencer Churchill 

The Rosie Project 

The Story of Civilization 

The Worldly Philosophers 

Uncle Tom's Cabin

Zen and the Art of Motorcycle Maintenance 

I cried while reading two of these books, one when I was about 11, and the second, just a few months ago. The most recently read of these books, Graeme Simsion's "The Rosie Project," made me laugh until I hurt. If you read it (about 2 hours), you may even learn a bit about some of your previously unexplored attributes.

Message:Here is a semi-complete (I say this because I'm positive there are other places) list of food establishments we must, as the youth profess, "hit up" during my time back in the States. While it is not necessary to exhaust this list I would like to "hit up" as many as possible so that I may look back upon this time and believe wholeheartedly that the 10 lbs I will inevitably gain from these adventures were, in fact, worth it. 

Watt's 
Merritt's 
La Farm 
Coquette 
BUFFALO WILD WINGS
Dame's 
Cafe Beyu (if only for a nostalgic drink)
Five Guys 
Med Deli
Founding Farmers (come to DC)
The lobstah truck (see above) 
Shiki (to kill this craving for American sushi)
Sugarland for a martini (nobody drives for three hours afterwards)
Lantern (for another nostalgic drink)
Irregardless Cafe 
Allen & Sons 

Please add to this list as you see fit. Upon hitting the tender age of 23 I can no longer ingest caffeine without disastrous side effects and I am sure that even the capabilities of my memory have been affected by the epidemic of "old age." 

Sayoko Sueyoshi

ID:501452010_10152318565742011
Name:Drinks and such
Story:N/A
Message:A very collected whiskey on the nose.

Nikka Yoichi 20
Single Malt (52%)
Purchased early 2014

My first bottle of Nikka thanks my frd bringing it all the way back! The thing with Nikka is, it's young and have quite some inconsistency between vintages.

Pale straw colored, it's coppery, malty, woodsy polish with slightly dark cherries in its reserved nose. The acrid attack on the palate quickly settle with tea, toffee and vanishing smoke. Sourly hints.

The backbone nested within its high alcohol contents is a pure, focused Japanese soul, so why not served undiluted to keep its structure? It's original, linear, no fancy.

I feel picky on the water source of this Yoichi, it doesn't have the organic mouthfeel of Suntory's whiskey. Then the finish feels subdued and a little disconnected.

As a NV 20 year whiskey that comes after some successful vintages, it struggle to be perfect. Don't get me wrong, it has a very lovely character. 92.

May the road rise up to meet you.
May the wind always be at your back.
May the sun shine warm upon your face,
and rains fall soft upon your fields.

May God hold you in the palm of His hand.

ID:629172885_10151533868402886
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:My one day trip to Coimbatore:
  After 13 years, I got a chance to take Cheran Express (err. Ahilyanagari express) to Coimbatore from Chennai. It was a welcome break from Chennai's scorching heat. It was at least 5 deg. Celsius cooler and heavy rains was icing on the cake.

Highlight of the trip was getting to meet HVR. Apparently, he is my wife's family friend and I got to meet him and his wife. He hasn't changed a bit at all. Same speed same sharpness. I wonder why he retired so early.

Next stop was to Peelamedu. I went to Pazhamudir nilayam first. PSP's bright smile from his photograph welcomed me. Apparently, he is their biggest customer till date - a record that has not been broken for 14 years. Sipping my grape juice, I stopped at CSE dept. I was looking for someone from the staff team whom I might recognize but to my surprise I bumped into Engels. He is now an associate prof. there. I got to spend some time with him. 

Many things have changed here. Building layout, foot over bridge etc. But one thing hasn't changed at all. And that still proves I was at PSG tech.

ID:708705302_10152032127220303
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

ID:742046082_10151787733886083
Name:India's north-east : an aesthetic portrait of proud India!
Story:N/A
Message:A paean and a message to the people of the north-east of India!

We are happy to note that our efforts to promote the north-east of India are bearing fruit!

From the initial days when Ms. Ambika Soni was the Minister of Tourism, when we won the National Tourism Award and the Incredible India award for our efforts to push the north-eastern region, we have had every conviction that the Seven Sister states are heavily under-represented in India's cultural and tourism fabric, in terms of higher educational opportunities, fast internet bandwith and IT infrastructure, highways and airports, SEZ's and IT parks, call centers and IIT's. Imagine if we equipped the north-east with just the opportunities given to political backyards such as Amethi and Rae Bareli - the millions of super-educated, fashionable, well-turned-out, English speaking Mizos, Manipuris, Arunachalis, Meghalayans, Nagas, Assamese and Tripurites would be able to compete more fairly with the rest of India and would clearly excel and bring pride to our country and the few remaining ignorant and casteist Indians would stop referring to them as 'chinkis' and using other derogatory terms simply because they feel complexed before them and fail to understand them. Heck, in the north-east of India, they don't even have BO (body odour) like some of the rest of us do!

So today's Times of India report confirming that tourist arrivals into the north-east have gone up in the past two years, with a spectacular 41% increase for Nagaland, is not only an affirmation of Ambika Soni's initial efforts, and tourism officials from these states (one name stands out to me - Lisapila Anar has done more for her state of Nagaland than anyone else I can think of), but of Wilderness Films India's untiring efforts to archive and bring to the rest of the world the wild, floral, vegetable, culinary, cultural, religious, sporting, adventurous and many other jewels that remain to be discovered in India's best kept secret - the Seven Sister states of the north-east!

And how can I not mention our dynamic new Tourism Secretary in the Government of India? Parvez Dewan is a walking talking encyclopedia on India (in particular Kashmir and the north-east). We have not seen such a competent man in tourism circles in ages... From this ITDC days to now, he has solely made the biggest contribution in pushing individual tourism projects and funding for the region. Parvez is probably the most published IAS officer and most well-travelled in the region. Here is a man who walks the walk. He actually visits the north-east, has more friends from there than all other parts of India put together and is virtually an ambassador for the Seven Sister states! Never before has India been better placed to benefit the north-east and gain from the investment, in the process...

Last month, we astutely predicted a massive fillip to north-eastern tourism as a result of the heavy devaluation of the Indian Rupee against all international currencies. This can only translate into increased tourism footfalls to the north-east as Indian tourists are fed-up of the usual destinations, Kashmir is once again on the boiling back-burner and Uttarakhand has been badly singed by the floods. The gainers will be ALL of the Seven Sister states and with the monsoons coming to an end, what better time to start making plans to head east...?

We are happy to report that we are seeing between 25, 000 and 50, 000 page views on our north-eastern video-clips, on a daily basis, on Youtube, and going by traffic statistics, much of this traffic arises from Europe and America. We are thus the LARGEST archive on north-east India, are bringing in the maximum traffic to the Seven Sister states and thus doing out bit for tourism in the region, and almost entirely without the help of either the central or the state governments!

Many people are writing in to us to help them plan out their north-east India travel itineraries, and we are helping them churn out plans for visits to the region. We are trying to be fair and democratic and not referring them to any particular travel agents but to the state's tourism departments. Look out for an exceptional turn-out at this year's Hornbill Festival in Kohima (December 2013), Sangai Festival in Imphal (November 2013) and Chapchar Kut in Aizawl (March 2014). We don't want any credit, but are happy to sit back in smug satisfaction as we see our carefully crafted strategies bearing fruit, for the region and the people that we love so much...

So let's see one once again!

India's north-east : an aesthetic portrait of proud India!

Remember what we wrote in May 2013? "North-east India comprises of the very best of India - the highest levels of literacy, the nicest folks, the oldest and deepest culture, a wide variety of religious beliefs, music and dance, a variety of tribes and communities - a wide palette of humanity, all contributing to the rich fabric of India.

And now welcome a greater penetration of tourism in the N-E as well! With the Rupee threatening to reach Rs. 70 to a dollar, instead of flying out to Thailand and Singapore or even Europe, why not fly down to Bagdogra and hit Sikkim, or Guwahati airport that can lead you into Meghalaya or even Arunachal, or then Aizawl for Mizoram, Agartala for Tripura, Dimapur for Nagaland or the (soon to be international!) airport of Imphal in Manipur! So come on over and see the discover the best-kept secrets of India!"

Message:Hi everyone,
We will be leaving our flat on the 1st of September and we are looking for someone to take over. The flat is 36m? with private bathroom and toilets, and we installed an IKEA kitchenette with electric plates and storage. It is part of a house with two neighbourgs, there is a common well furnished kitchen upstairs that you can also use if you want to cook with gas, as well as another bathroom. Washing machine and dryer are provided and free to use. 
The flat is located on Boterdiep, which is less than 5 minutes walking from Martini tower and 10 minutes biking from Zernike. There are lots of shops around (two AH 3 and 5 min walking, Jumbo 5 min walking, Asian shop 7 min walking...). 
The price is 526/month for one person and 50 more for two persons including utilities and internet. It is particularily well suited for a couple, but only allows one registration to the city hall (only a problem if your visa specifies that).
We would like to sell our furnitures for a reasonable price. This includes almost everything seen in the pictures (kitchen block + kitchen ustensiles, big fridge with freezer, closet, table, sofa chairs, oven, vaccum cleaner...).
There is an agency fee of ~516? as well as a deposit of one month rent.
Don't hesitate to PM for more information! Cheers

Name:Timeline Photos

ID:1249020124_10202797337195042
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Dennard tagged me to list 10 books that have influenced my life or something like that, so:

1) I Am A Bunny - Ole Risom, Richard Scarry - My first book that I read on my own.

2) Amelia Bedelia - Peggy Parish - You think my puns are bad? Blame it on Amelia Bedelia.

3) Aliens Ate My Homework - Bruce Coville - None of those girly girl books for me, as a fifth-grader I was obsessed with books about extraterrestrials.

4) The I Hate Mathematics! Book - Marilyn Burns, Martha Weston - I thought times tables and such were terribly boring, but this book opened my mind about what math could be. Happy to say I've converted into a proud math lover. :)

5) The Giver - Lois Lowry - One of my all-time favorites, I've read it three times at least.

6) A Wrinkle In Time - Madeleine L'Engle - It's not every day that a touching brother-sister story meets fifth-dimension-travel sci-fi; the scenes from this book have always stayed with me.

7) The Perks of Being a Wallflower - Stephen Chbosky - Favorite book for a while, though it's hard to identify a particular reason. Just one of those books that captures adolescence, and plus, the music is great.

8) Head First Design Patterns - Eric Freeman, Bert Bates, Kathy Sierra, Elisabeth Robson - Completely changed my perspective on software design, plus was a ridiculously entertaining read.

9) Brave New World - Aldous Huxley - Probably the dystopian novel that rings the most true in today's world. It has really shaped the way I see all the "progress" around me, especially here in Silicon Valley.

10) The Giving Tree - Shel Silverstein - The shortest book ever to rip your heart out. Moral: Hug your mom.

ID:1391340229_10202591145845131
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:There was an article quoting a student at a university. This is the quote: 

"While everyone condemns sexual assault, there seems to be an assumption among female students that they shouldn't have to protect themselves by avoiding drunkenness [to an extent where any level of decision making is not possible anymore] ... We have to encourage people not to take on undue risk. [While also recognizing that a victim remains a victim and deserves recognition of such]"

The article in which the quote appeared, unquestioningly condemned the quote. 

I and another reader who commented understood the quote as it reads now with the bracketed sections added. The other reader intelligently re-enforced that if interpreted in such a way, it was a fair point to make. Quote follows:

"It is ignorant to call some one a victim blamer for saying something along the lines of make better decisions to avoid negative outcomes. If you tell someone they shouldn't stick their hand in fire because it will hurt them, you are not a victim blamer, you simply are warning them of a danger that is known to happen under specific circumstances based on history. The person who is burned should not be at no fault at all because put themselves in the particular circumstances were the negative outcome occurs often. To be clear none of what I just said is justification for rape, it is not in defense of the rapist, and most of all it is not victim blaming. I'd also like to add that I personally believe all rapists should be tortured until death."

Cue tons of people ignorantly flaming him for being a pig, when it was clear, that he supported women's rights, and was most definitely not a pig. Rather than jump into discussion there, attempting to convince enraged people of something they did not want to hear, I decided to lay out my thoughts here in a fresh environment.

This is In response to a type of statement, that I commonly see, stating people should have no responsibility for their actions/decisions as long as someone else happens to do something terrible to them.

Someone doing something terrible is THE SAME THING as something terrible happening (e.g. a house fire, or car crash). These terrible things are part of the world, and will happen no matter how much we try to wish that they won't.

Do these certain women really believe that women should have no responsibility for decisions they make ((or lack thereof)) under the influence? Would it be any different if the girl drank and made the decision to get into a car with her guy friend driving--who is also inebriated--and they both got in a crash and died? Would she have made that stupid decision if she was sober or less intoxicated? Probably not. When you drink, you cannot look out for yourself or make smart decisions. Who cares who's fucking fault it is. 

Say some piece of trash rapist does not make the right choice and does attempt a rape--which btw is disgusting and inexcusable--some women are saying that it would NOT be a good thing to be able to stop that? If it is a good thing to be able to avoid that, then how is that not automatically partial responsibility for your own decisions?

I wish that all of a sudden magically somehow, all of the women getting on the internet complaining about bad people and bad culture--specifically rape culture--would somehow make those bad things cease to exist. Because, really, how nice would it be if the world was void of bad things? 

However, that is an incredibly naive and pathetic approach. And that goes for any person who thinks along such lines. The world is bad, and full of bad shit. Get over the fact that you might have to find your own ways to limit the effects of such evil. But, you know what, fine... go ahead and accept no responsibility for ensuring--on your own terms--that you won't have to experience the effects of all the bad stuff, and see how much effect that has in making the bad things bow down to that extremely brave sentiment and decide to leave you alone. *eyeroll*

The world is not and never will be a utopia void of evil and bad will. Because of that you automatically have responsibility for your own well being. If you disagree, just sit down and let the world take care of you. See how quickly you rot in one place when you do not take care of yourself, because essentially that is what you are arguing for by claiming no responsibility...and no rape, is not an extenuating circumstance... it lives alongside every other terrible misfortune that could happen to a person.

Message:Why should I have to be subjected to these fat women in skimpy clothes? Fat people need to realize that in order to be seen beautifully, they cannot force their scantily clad image on people who simply will never be attracted to them. You cannot force any action/reaction, let alone a positive action/reaction. And with that rant, here is a fable that has been part of my life for many years. I wish I had embraced it sooner than the past couple years of my life.

=========================================================

THE WIND and the Sun were disputing which was the stronger. Suddenly they saw a traveller coming down the road, and the Sun said: ?I see a way to decide our dispute. Whichever of us can cause that traveller to take off his cloak shall be regarded as the stronger You begin.? So the Sun retired behind a cloud, and the Wind began to blow as hard as it could upon the traveller. But the harder he blew the more closely did the traveller wrap his cloak round him, till at last the Wind had to give up in despair. Then the Sun came out and shone in all his glory upon the traveller, who soon found it too hot to walk with his cloak on.
?KINDNESS EFFECTS MORE THAN SEVERITY.? (or how I see it, "INVITE CHANGE; DO NOT FORCE IT.")

=========================================================

"Are you single?" [this was on a sign being held up by a female as an example of harassment she received]

"Why can't you men just leave us alone when we are out on the street." [a response to the article by a woman frustrated by the (note) VERY real problem of street harassment]

Anyone who supports this idea that attempting to start a conversation regarding dating/relationship with a stranger, is harassment needs to get their entitlement in check.

The world is a wonderful place with tons of wonderful people. If a bunch of rules meant to protect women end up restricting human interaction, there is a problem. Men should not have to be afraid to approach women, and women should not have to assume that all men intend to take what they want. 

I personally treat everyone with respect. and I refuse to accept all of these rules that do nothing but get us closer to living under Sharia...restrictions on every aspect of interaction in order to keep things "safe" and "moral." Do you want a free, joyful society where the members act freely and responsibly, where there are some bad people? The book "Anatomy of Peace" comes to mind. A decent amount of the book actually talks about the conflict that has been present for so long in Gaza as an example of how we use others as objects in order to justify our own acts of war. It is human nature to protect ourselves from harm, both emotional and physical. This is why we can do such inhumane things to our enemies, because there is no room for empathizing with an enemy. The enemy is a harmful object, no longer a person or a peoples. Some quotes in light of my extreme disappointment regarding the situation.

=========================================================

?There is a question I have learned to ask myself when I am feeling bothered about others: am I holding myself to the same standard I am demanding of them?? 
? Arbinger Institute, The Anatomy of Peace

?Most wars between individuals are of the 'cold' rather than the 'hot' variety---lingering resentment, for example, grudges long held, resources clutched rather than shared, help not offered. These are the acts of war that most threaten our homes and workplaces.? 
? Arbinger Institute, The Anatomy of Peace

?The more sure I am that I'm right, the more likely I will actually be mistaken. My need to be right makes it more likely that I will be wrong! Likewise, the more sure I am that I am mistreated, the more likely I am to miss ways that I am mistreating others myself. My need for justification obscures the truth.? 
? Arbinger Institute, The Anatomy of Peace

?...when I betray myself, others' faults become immediately inflated in my heart and mind. I begin to 'horribilize' others. That is, I begin to make them out to be worse than they really are. And I do this because the worse they are, the more justified I feel.? 
? Arbinger Institute, The Anatomy of Peace

=========================================================

I wish Israel and Palestine would swallow the pride and sacrifice the zealous goals, realize that all involved are humans after all. PEOPLE, with feelings and lives.

ID:1396410136_10201358343786019
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Since you keep asking me, haha.

"Gluten is a protein in wheat and grains.  ALL grains have gluten in them. So wheat, barley, rye, corn, rice, etc.  Wheat gluten is by far the worst due to its chemical structure.  Its been so hybridized that our bodies don't understand it when it gets digested so its easy for our bodies to create antibodies against it.  Hence, we feel like crap.  Bloated, brain fog, weight gain, a zillion other potential issues.  Most processed and boxed foods, dressings, mixes, and pre-made items have gluten in it.   Gluten is [especially] used for baking items.  Its the 'glue' in the dough."  (Taken from my nutritionist/health-freak friend.)

So I guess I should say I'm wheat gluten-free (or at least I try to be).

Name:null
Story:"I am not adverting here to the alleged privacy of experience to its possessor. The point of view in question
is not one accessible only to a single individual. Rather it is a type. It is often possible to take up a point of
view other than one's own, so the comprehension of such facts is not limited to one's own case. There is a
sense in which phenomenological facts are perfectly objective: one person can know or say of another
what the quality of the other's experience is. They are subjective, however, in the sense that even this
objective ascription of experience is possible only for someone sufficiently similar to the object of
ascription to be able to adopt his point of view?to understand the ascription in the first person as well as
in the third, so to speak. The more different from oneself the other experiencer is, the less success one can
expect with this enterprise. In our own case we occupy the relevant point of view, but we will have as
much difficulty understanding our own experience properly if we approach it from another point of view
as we would if we tried to understand the experience of another species without taking up its point of 
view" on Wilson Wong's timeline.

Name:Secure ID: Checklist of all Accepted Documents - Department of Driver Services
Story:N/A
Message:The worst way an immigrant could be treated by a country in which they contribute talent, youth and dilligent work:

On Georgia DDS website: http://www.dds.ga.gov/secureid/accepteddocs.aspx

Passport+Visa+I-94+I-797+I-20=primary identification
Social Security Card=proof of social security number
utility bill+unexpired license=proof of residency

Me: Present all above documents and request renewal.
Staff1: We cannot do it.
Me: try to explain the documents do establish my legal presence and identity.
Staff1: You can pay $20 to renew, but we cannot do it.
Me: But I think I have provide all documents to justify my legal presense during the period I request my driver license to be extended. Why it cannot be done?
Staff1: We cannot do it. (turn to staff at next window) We cannot, right?Staff2: No, we cannot.
Me: But if you agree I am legally present in states, I should be able to renew my license.
Staff1: I told you we cannot do it. It's over. You want me to call a state patron?
<shocked, why a state patron is in need at this point?>
Me: Well, at least you should let me know why I cannot get the license renewed.
Staff1: We just cannot.
Me: If you are not quite able to explain the reason, may I talk to a supervisor on this case?
Staff1: (point to staff2) She is a supervisor and she told you we cannot. You wanna talk to her?
Staff2: I told you we cannot.
Me: But why?
Staff2: We just cannot. There's no use to argue. 
<Did I argue? I just try to get a reason like "you miss document x, y, z" or "your document a, b, c is not valid" or "according to state regulation u, v, w, we don't extend license in this situation">
Me: Then I probably need to talk to your(staff2's) supervisor. I need to know the reason.
Staff1: You really want me to call the state patron, right? Look at all these people waiting. If you don't leave, I will call the state patron.
<Up till this point, I did not have any aggressive behavior, even no aggressive words. Why a state patron is in need?>

I am an F-1 student in the past 5 years and my study ends on Aug 1st, 2013. I recently got I-797A, change of status notice, on approval of upcoming H-1B status starting Oct 1st, 2013.

According to the code of federal regulation and the guidance I received from government and school immigration officer, I am considered legally present in U.S. with a comment on page 3 of my I-20 until Sep 30th, 2013. So I try to request an extension on my driver's license with these documents.

I fully understand that this may be a rare case and kindly try to present the information I know to Athens DDS staffs. However, I get no listening and many threats during this procedure. All what I try to know is why the case cannot be processed, but I get no help on this. I feel being discriminated as an immigrant throughout the whole procedure.

I hope you could pay attention to this case, not only for the benefit of future talented immigrants but also for the interest to this country.

Message:THANKS FOR COMING TO DUMPLING NIGHT!!! :) And shout out to the best dumpling chef, Qianli Wang, and CJ Yoon,  Chuner Guo, Dalen Kuang, Christopher Mejias, Brooke Liang, and Phuong for doing a ton of work prepping and cleaning. Hope you guys had as much fun as I did!! 

For anyone who was asking for the recipe, here's a list of ingredients (sorry we're not very good at measurements): 

Dough: flour, water, salt (optional) 

Pork filling: ground pork, egg, cabbage (chop really small, then squeeze water out), green onion, cilantro, soy sauce, sesame oil, vegetable oil, pepper, salt 

Veggie filling: shiitake mushrooms, carrots, cabbage, green onion, soy sauce, sesame oil, pepper, salt

Story:Yin Cen was tagged in Jie Gao's photo.
Message:N/A
ID:100001043113693_771080102936753
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

ID:100002080773443_532583273487694
Name:Non-Uniform Random Variate Generation
Story:N/A
Message:When I wrote this book in 1986, I had to argue long and hard with Springer Verlag to publish it. They printed a small number of copies, and never bothered with a second printing, even though, surprisingly, there seemed to be some continued demand for the book. I have asked Springer to print more copies, but they flatly refused, unless I was willing to publish a second edition with them in the near future. Burnt once, why would I trust them with a second edition? Also, I figured that since Springer had gross income about 500,000 US dollars from my books with them, that they would be more generous with their royalties and more responsive to demands for second printings. The contrary is true in fact: royalties are decreasing (they stand now at 7.5% per book), and I feel that I am just one of the many academic rape victims.

As the book is out of print, the copyright and ownership is mine, so I do with it what I want. On these web pages, you will find a fine scan of my book in text searchable PDF format (thanks, HK). This is the original text. A list of errata is here.

Furthermore, I give anyone the permission, even without asking me, to take these PDF files to a printer, print as many copies as you like, and sell them for profit. If you would like me to advertise the sales points of the hard copies, please let me know. To the libraries: Please do not charge patrons for copying this book. I grant everyone the right to copy at will, for free.       http://luc.devroye.org/rnbookindex.html

ID:100002209942621_622660121150980
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

ID:100002637281786_683689975062239
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:We are SO excited for this month, not only because it is the month of sweaters, scarves, boots, and pumpkin-flavored everything, but because it is Breast Cancer Awareness Month! In the effort to raise funds for a cause that we truly hold close to our hearts, the sisters of UNC aKDPhi, along with thousands of other sisters across the nation, will be walking/running/biking #100miles to end Breast Cancer. We will be working hard all month to raise awareness of this prevalent disease and to raise funds in hopes of finding a cure.

Lucky for you, you can help the cause by ordering off the donation menu at Spicy 9 on Franklin St!! For this entire month, all proceeds made from that menu will be going to our national philanthropy - Avon Breast Cancer Crusade. You can make all the difference by simply enjoying a roll of sushi.

Also, we are taking a second round of orders for our BCA tanks, so make sure to order one if you missed your chance earlier! Again, all proceeds will be going to Avon. (https://www.facebook.com/events/1534384796792206/)

Last but not least, we will be hosting our 12th annual Charity Ball on October 11th from 7-9PM in the Great Hall. This has always been one of our biggest, and most successful events, so come out and see what we have planned for you! (https://www.facebook.com/events/718164144925030/)

We know that with your help, we will be able to make a huge impact by the end of the month. Follow us on social media to keep up with our journey this month as we strive to save lives.

#aKDPhindacure2014

alpha Kappa Delta Phi Sorority, Inc.
alpha Kappa Delta Phi National Alumnae Association

ID:100002813248009_454019568035147
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

Message:Just to refresh the universal facts we know:

    During his own Google interview, Jeff Dean was asked the  implications if P=NP were true.  He said, "P = 0 or N = 1." Then, before  the interviewer had even finished laughing, Jeff examined Google?s  public certificate and wrote the private key on the whiteboard.
    Compilers don?t warn Jeff Dean.   Jeff Dean warns compilers.
    The rate at which Jeff Dean produces code jumped by a factor of 40  in late 2000 when he upgraded his keyboard to USB 2.0.
    Jeff Dean builds his code before committing it, but only to check for compiler and linker bugs.
    When Jeff Dean has an ergonomic evaluation, it is for the protection of his keyboard.
    All pointers point to Jeff Dean.
    gcc -O4 emails your code to Jeff Dean for a rewrite.
    Jeff Dean once failed a Turing test when he correctly identified the 203rd Fibonacci number in less than a second."
    The speed of light in a vacuum used to be about 35 mph. Then Jeff Dean spent a weekend optimizing physics."
    Jeff Dean was born on December 31, 1969 at 11:48 PM. It took him twelve minutes to implement his first time counter."
    Jeff Dean eschews both Emacs and VI. He types his code into zcat, because it's faster that way.
    When Jeff Dean sends an ethernet frame there are no collisions because the competing frames retreat back up into the buffer memory on their source nic.
    Unsatisfied with constant time, Jeff Dean created the world's first O(1/n) algorithm.
    When Jeff Dean goes on vacation, production services across Google mysteriously stop working within a few days. This is actually true.
    Jeff Dean was forced to invent asynchronous APIs one day when he optimized a function so that it returned before it was invoked.
    When Jeff Dean designs software, he first codes the binary and then writes the source as documentation.
    Jeff Dean wrote an O(n^2) algorithm once. It was for the Traveling Salesman Problem.
    Jeff Dean once implemented a web server in a single printf() call. Other engineers added thousands of lines of explanatory comments but still don't understand exactly how it works. Today that program is the front-end to Google Search.
    True: Jeff once simultaneously reduced all binary sizes by 3% AND raised the severity of a previously known low-priority python bug to critical-priority in a single change that contained no python code.
    Jeff Dean can beat you at connect four. In three moves.
    When your code has undefined behavior, you get a seg fault and corrupted data. When Jeff Dean's code has undefined behavior, a unicorn rides in on a rainbow and gives everybody free ice cream.
    When Jeff Dean fires up the profiler, loops unroll themselves in fear.
    Jeff Dean is still waiting for mathematicians to discover the joke he hid in the digits of PI.
    Jeff Dean's keyboard has two keys: 1 and 0.
    When Jeff has trouble sleeping, he Mapreduces sheep.
    When Jeff Dean listens to mp3s, he just cats them to /dev/dsp and does the decoding in his head.
    When Graham Bell invented the telephone, he saw a missed call from Jeff Dean.
    Jeff Dean's watch displays seconds since January 1st, 1970. He is never late.
    Jeff starts his programming sessions with 'cat > /dev/mem'.
    One day Jeff Dean grabbed his Etch-a-Sketch instead of his laptop on his way out the door. On his way back home to get his real laptop, he programmed the Etch-a-Sketch to play Tetris.

ID:100006641705075_712707735416524
Name:null
Story:Katrina Wertz posted an event to Facss China's timeline.
Message:This month of February, Carolina China Network is excited to present a discussion entitled China & Africa: Define the Relationship on Friday, February 28th from 4-5pm in Union Room 3206.  We are keen on exposing students on our campus to the myriad of reasons why China has turned attention to Africa?s continent and what opportunities and consequences have come about.  The short one-hour event will be a great chance to come together and eat free Chinese dumplings and discuss economic, diplomatic, and cultural collaborations from a high-level viewpoint.  Our goal is for each person in the room to hear, share, and learn something new about the Sino-Africa relationship that they may not have heard or considered before, and to meet someone in the room that you could continue the conversation with beyond this event!

    ???????????????? ???????????????? ??????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????

 

 

    Jim Morgan  was named  President  and CEO  of Krispy  Kreme Doughnuts, Inc. in January 2008. Mr. Morgan has been a member of the Krispy  Kreme  Board  of Directors  since  2000  and was elected its Chairman in 2005.

 

    Mr. Morgan served as Chairman and CEO of Wachovia Securities following the acquisition of Interstate/Johnson Lane, Inc. (IJL) by Wachovia  Corporation.   He  also  served  as Chairman  and  CEO of Interstate/Johnson Lane, Inc.. Mr. Morgan is a past member of the Securities Industry Association Board of Directors and the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) regional firms committee, and is currently on the Board of Directors of Coca-Coca Bottling Company Consolidated. Mr. Morgan has more than 40 years of business experience and is a

1969 graduate of Vanderbilt University. He also served as a lieutenant in the U.S. Navy.
